And holding the bridle of his horse, out of , reverence for the blessed Peter, we performed for him the duty of squire; decreeing that all his successors, and they alone, use < this same tiara in processions in imitation of our power.'’

Does not this fable-fabricator seem to blunder, not through imprudence, but deliberately and of set purpose, and so as to offer handles for catching him? In the same passage he says both that the Lord's resurrection is represented by the tiara, and that it is an imitation of Caesar’s power; two things which differ most widely from each other.
